<section class="card">
  <h2>Northwest Territories Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Gardening in the Northwest Territories is defined by extremes: very long summer daylight,
    short frost-free windows, and rapid seasonal transitions. While the calendar season is brief,
    intense sunlight can support surprisingly strong growth when crops are chosen carefully.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Daylength is your advantage</h3>
  <p>
    Peak summer brings extended daylight hours that drive rapid vegetative growth.
    Leafy greens, brassicas, and root crops often perform exceptionally well despite the short season.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’re working within a tight window, this overview of
    <a href="/guides/what-crops-grow-in-short-growing-seasons/">
      crops that grow well in short seasons
    </a>
    can help guide variety selection.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Frost risk frames the entire plan</h3>
  <p>
    Late spring frost can linger, and fall frost can return quickly. Warm-season crops must be
    started early and protected to have a realistic chance of maturing.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    For a deeper look at how frost dates and heat accumulation interact,
    see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">
      how frost dates and growing degree days work together
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Soil warming can lag behind air temperatures</h3>
  <p>
    Even when daytime highs look promising, soil temperatures may remain too cool for direct-seeding
    warm crops. Raised beds and dark mulches can help accelerate warming.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Microclimates make a measurable difference</h3>
  <p>
    South-facing walls, wind protection, and well-drained sites often outperform exposed open ground.
    In northern climates, small differences in exposure can translate into meaningful gains.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Use frost dates to define your outer boundaries.</li>
    <li>Prioritize quick-maturing and cold-tolerant crops.</li>
    <li>Add protection if attempting heat-loving varieties.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In the Northwest Territories, success comes from crop selection, smart protection,
    and making full use of peak summer daylight.
  </p>
</section>